\begin_layout Standard
In the case of an uncountably infinite vector space the basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\KET q\right)_{q\in\mathbb{R}}$
\end_inset

 can be written as a function of a real variable.
 The representation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\KET{\psi}$
\end_inset

 then is an infinite sum, that is an integral
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\KET{\psi} & =\int\psi\left(q\right)\KET q\dd q
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and a complete and orthonormal basis is characterized by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle q,q'\right\rangle =\delta\left(q-q'\right)$
\end_inset

.
