\emph on
Adjoint
\emph default
: For each Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 there is another Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}^{*}$
\end_inset

 called 
\emph on
dual
\emph default
, with elements 
\begin_inset Formula $\bra f\in\mathcal{H}^{*}$
\end_inset

, which are 
\noun on
linear functionals
\noun default
 acting on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\BRA f:\mathcal{H} & \to\mathbb{C}\\
\KET{\psi} & \mapsto\BraKet{f|\psi}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\BraKet{\psi|\phi}$
\end_inset

 is called 
\emph on
bracket
\emph default
.
 Riesz theorem says, that there is a 
\noun on
one to one
\noun default
 correspondence between 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}^{*}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\fall_{\KET{\psi}\in\mathcal{H}} & \ \exs_{\BRA{\psi}\in\mathcal{H}^{*}}\ \fall_{\KET{\phi}\in\mathcal{H}}\ :\ \BraKet{\psi|\phi}=\left\langle \psi,\phi\right\rangle ,\norm{\BRA{\psi}}=\norm{\KET{\psi}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The so associated 
\begin_inset Formula $\BRA{\psi}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\emph on
adjoint
\emph default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\KET{\psi}$
\end_inset

, called 
\emph on
bra
\emph default
, and we write: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
^{\dagger}:\mathcal{H} & \to\mathcal{H}^{*}\\
\KET{\psi} & \mapsto\left(\KET{\psi}\right)^{\dagger}=\BRA{\psi}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The function 
\begin_inset Formula $^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

 is semilinear, that means for 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\KET{\psi},\KET{\phi}\in\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left(a\KET{\psi}+b\KET{\phi}\right)^{\dagger} & =a^{*}\BRA{\psi}+b^{*}\BRA{\phi}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

